04326nam a22005535i 9780231557856DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315578567 a10.7312/toke209262doi  a(DE-B1597)665670  a(OCoLC)1396937658  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aJK2281b.T65 2023 7aSOC0700002bisacsh04a324.7089/96073223/eng/202304131 aTokeshi, Matthew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCampaigning While Black :bBlack Candidates, White Majorities, and the Quest for Political Office /cMatthew Tokeshi. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource :b35 B&w charts and graphs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1. WHY ARE BLACK GOVERNORS AND U.S. SENATORS SO RARE? RACIAL BIAS AGAINST BLACK CHALLENGERS, 2000– 2020 -- t2. THE RACIALIZATION OF BLACK CANDIDATES -- t3. THE RESPONSE OF BLACK CANDIDATES -- t4. THE DEVAL PATRICK AND HAROLD FORD JR. CAMPAIGNS OF 2006 -- t5. THE 2013 CORY BOOKER AND 2014 ANTHONY BROWN CAMPAIGNS -- t6. WHEN BLACK WOMEN RUN: THE 2018 STACEY ABRAMS AND 2020 KAMALA HARRIS CAMPAIGNS -- t7. THE BOOKER EXPERIMENT -- t8. THE CRIMINAL PARDON EXPERIMENT -- tCONCLUSION -- tAppendixes -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEven today, Black politicians rarely hold the most powerful elected offices one step below the presidency: governor and U.S. senator. While about 11 percent of the electorate is Black, only 3 percent of senators and 2 percent of governors are Black. Only ten Black Americans have been elected to these offices since Reconstruction, and forty-two states have never elected a Black governor or U.S. senator. Why is it so rare for Black candidates to win elections for these offices?Matthew Tokeshi examines the campaigns of every Black challenger for those offices from 2000 through 2020 and points to the significant effects of racial appeals to white voters. He demonstrates that Black candidates consistently face more attacks on stereotypically anti-Black themes such as crime, sexual misbehavior, and economic redistribution than comparable white candidates. Such attacks diminish their support among the large number of white voters with ambivalent or negative attitudes toward Blacks. However, despite this formidable hurdle, Black candidates can in some circumstances mitigate the effects of negative racial messages.Presenting timely new evidence on the racial dynamics that shape electoral politics in the United States, Campaigning While Black exposes the unique obstacles facing Black candidates and highlights ways that these barriers can be overcome.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican American politicianszUnited StatesxPublic opinion. 0aPolitical campaignszUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aRace discriminationxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aRacismxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aWhite peoplezUnited StatesxAttitudesxHistoryy21st century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Race & Ethnic Relations.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311074967040uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/toke2092640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231557856423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231557856/original  a978-3-11-074967-0  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles